<TEXT>
oklahoma became the first state in the 
nation to put a limit on the length of service of state legislators 
by giving overwhelming approval tuesday to a constitutional 
amendment 
the amendment which becomes effective jan 1 puts a lifetime 
cap of 12 years on legislative service legislators currently in 
office will be allowed to serve 12 more years 
with 95 percent of the precincts reporting yes votes 
outnumbered nos by 427347 to 205023 or 68 percent to 32 
percent 
tulsa businessman lloyd noble ii backed the circulation of an 
initiative petition to get the issue on the ballot he contended 
that the term limitation was needed to keep legislators from 
becoming entrenched in office and beholden to vested interests 
instead of the people they were supposed to serve 
opponents argued that a remedy already was available the 
ballot box they pointed out that only 16 members of the 48member 
state senate and 14 of the 101 house members had 12 or more years 
of service at the end of the 1990 legislative session 
the opponents also argued that voters would be giving up some of 
their rights by approving the term limitation bill but most 
observers had predicted from the outset it would pass particularly 
after the people approved another state question in 1989 that 
sharply limited the time the legislature can remain in session 
although state legislators elected this year will take office in 
november noble said he believed the 12year limit would apply to 
them 
colorado and california will vote on term limitation proposals 
nov 6 according to the national council of state legislatures 
similar legislation has been introduced in florida and new york 
the council said 
</TEXT>
