<TEXT>
bush administration and congressional budget 
negotiators were an impasse late monday after both sides made new 
offers that still left them far apart in the area of new taxes and 
with important disagreements over spending cuts 
congressional leaders of both parties and top administration 
aides planned to abandon the talks at nearby andrews air force base 
and instead were scheduled to meet at the us capitol on tuesday 
in an attempt to get the discussions going again 
bargainers said they were not giving up hope that a 
deficitcutting deal could ultimately be reached but they 
expressed uncertainty over how that could be done 
its not quite an impasse but its pretty close to one said 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan after 10 grueling days 
there are still major differences on dozens of issues all the way 
from a for agriculture to z for enterprise zones 
its going to be tough but its still not impossible and no 
one is giving up dole continued the problem is were running 
out of time 
asked if the talks had collapsed sen phil gramm rtexas 
another negotiator said no but at this point weve reached an 
impasse were apart on every major area 
a democratic official involved in the talks speaking on 
condition of anonymity declined to call the bargaining at an 
impasse he said the only remaining areas of discord was over 
president bushs insistence that the package include a cut in the 
capital gains tax 
the lawmakers and administration officials had met for the last 
10 days at andrews in hopes the isolation from capitol hill might 
help them reach an agreement on ways to ease the deficit 
bush earlier monday called on the bargainers to complete a 
deficitreduction package but reiterated that he wanted a capital 
gains tax cut to be part of the deal 
weve made some headway recently in budget talks bush told 
reporters but it really is time now to get an agreement now i 
think we owe that to the american people 
negotiators at the talks which entered their tenth day have 
said the fight between democrats and republicans over reducing the 
capital gains tax rate is the key dispute blocking an agreement 
republicans have pushed to reduce that tax which is charged on 
the profits from the sales of property arguing that it would 
stimulate the economy but democrats have said the proposal would 
help almost exclusively the wealthy and have insisted that if it 
is included in the package there must also be a tax rate hike for 
the rich 
the bargainers meeting at andrews om nearby maryland swapped 
new budget cutting offers late monday both packages were aimed at 
reducing the deficit by about 50 billion next year and by 500 
billion through 1995 the two sides both wanted about 25 billion 
of the savings next year to come from new taxes and fees 
but the democrat offer was contingent on not having a capital 
gains cut as part of the package while the republican offer 
contained the cut and offset it by eliminating the deduction for 
state and local taxes for people earning more than 200000 
annually said one official close to the talks 
but republicans said there were major additional differences 
between the two sides that had caused the andrews talks to end 
they complained that while their package cut defense spending by 
170 billion over five years the democratic plan specified cuts of 
only 10 billion next year and 23 billion in fiscal 1992 the 
reductions for the three years beyond that were left unclear 
in recent days democrats had offered to cut military spending 
by 200 billion over the next five years 
republicans also complained that democrats were not willing to 
cut domestic programs deeply enough gop bargainers wanted to pare 
benefit programs like medicare by 1233 billion over the money 
they would need to stay even with inflation over the next five 
years democrats wanted to limit the cut to 1206 billion 
unless a deficitcutting package is in place by oct 1 the 
beginning of the next fiscal year the grammrudman law will 
automatically trigger about 100 billion in cuts in the 12 
trillion federal budget an amount considered high enough to 
seriously disrupt government operations 
there hasnt been one darn thing since we started that anybody 
has agreed on complained one of the bargainers rep silvio 
conte rmass earlier monday 
conte and house minority leader robert michel rill said some 
lawmakers are beginning to discuss legislation that would 
temporarily postpone the grammrudman spending cuts unless a budget 
deal is worked out both men said they opposed the idea but 
declined to say who was considering it 
ever since making it an issue during his 1988 election campaign 
bush has pushed to lower the top tax rate on capital gains the 
profits from the sale of property he has argued that a reduction 
would invigorate the economy by encouraging people to sell 
democrats have labeled the proposal a boon to the wealthy that 
would lower government revenues in the long run they have said 
that if the tax cut is to be included in a deficitcutting package 
they want it accompanied by higher income tax rates on the rich 
without a budget deal next years shortfall is expected to 
exceed 250 billion which would be the highest mark ever 
</TEXT>
