<TEXT>
nearly a year after an earthquake killed 67 
people and jolted nationwide tv viewers expecting the world series 
san franciscos supervisors still enter their chambers through an 
archway braced by timbers 
the embarcadero freeway is still deserted weeds sprouting from 
cracked concrete an estimated 1000 people left homeless by the 
71magnitude tremor sleep in doorways and shelters while the city 
negotiates redevelopment funds to rebuild hotels 
in santa cruz a seaside tourist town eight miles from the oct 
17 quakes epicenter chainlink fences ring downtown craters where 
the shuddering earth crumbled victorian buildings cracking 
colonnades and toppling turrets 
from san francisco to watsonville businesses homes and 
freeways severely damaged by the loma prieta quake remain in ruins 
and officials estimate it will be five to 10 years before the worst 
of the 7 billion10 billion damage is repaired 
none of the agencies involved was willing to estimate the final 
price tag which will include seismic renovations to protect 
against the the really big one 
its one of the most depressing things ive ever been through 
in my life its like it was nuclear bombed all the buildings are 
gone i can imagine going through world war ii and coming home 
to see your city totally destroyed said bob shepherd he was 
santa cruz city finance manager until he resigned aug 17 to teach 
only one of the 15 buildings demolished in the town centerpiece 
pacific garden mall is under construction five others have 
permits said ceil cerillo executive director of the citys 
redevelopment agency 
more than 35 businesses sell their wares out of six tent 
pavilions 
ten miles south in watsonville a town of migrant field hands 
and cannery workers the gutted main street has barely begun to 
revive the largest retailer fords department store announced in 
midaugust it will rebuild with help from federal emergency 
management agency funds 
in oakland where the quake stunned a downtown revitalization 
effort several blocks of stores and office buildings remain 
boarded up 
oakland city hall which dates to 1914 is ringed with 
scaffolding and closed to the public while the city dickers with 
fema over how much of the 90 million renovation the agency will 
reimburse 
san francisco officials wont begin the 100 million repair of 
the beaux arts city hall until they settle with fema 
there is still no agreement its stupid to work on our 
buildings while were negotiating whats eligible wed have 
removed the evidence said tom jones of the mayors office of 
community development and housing 
drivers in and out of the city continue to face traffic jams on 
us 101 and interstate 280 sections of which remain closed the 
embarcadero the lifeline to chinatown and north beach nightclubs 
remains a hulking ruin while the city decides whether to replace it 
with an underground expressway 
repairs to these roads are estimated at 160 million that does 
not include 100 million to replace interstate 880s cypress 
overpass where 42 of the quake victims died after it collapsed 
when the freeways reopen well be the foremost engineers in 
the world on earthquake repairs we want to do it right safety is 
the main issue said greg bayol spokesman for the state 
department of transportation 
some homeowners in san franciscos heavily damaged marina 
district where only two of 54 demolished buildings have been 
reoccupied found 500000 small business administration loans too 
little too late 
one woman interviewed by the city received word she was eligible 
for a nointerest 20year loan from caldap a state program one 
day after she agreed to sell her 25 million property for 1 
million to pay her note 
the earthquake happened at the same time as the savings and 
loan crisis said jones most lenders were willing to forgive 
one or two months but when the crisis hit the lenders starting 
calling their loans 
owners of transient hotels in oakland and san francisco found 
sba loans inadequate to repair the dilapidated buildings that 
housed an estimated 2500 elderly mentally disabled and poor 
people left permanently homeless by the quake 
officials estimate it will be five years before the freeways are 
restored and at least three years before hotels are rebuilt with 
help of emergency redevelopment funds said bill rumpf chief of 
san franciscos redevelopment agency 
the process takes months and years said henry renteria 
oaklands head of emergency services in whittier and coalinga 
their earthquakes were years ago and there are still buildings with 
issues not resolved 
