the 265th quartermaster detachment of the south 
carolina national guard is one of the reserve units called up for 
duty in saudi arabia national writer fred bayles has been with the 
14 guardsmen as they trained and deployed to the mideast 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
no one stays at this assembly area for 
more than a day the sergeant major explained except that a day 
can sometimes last two weeks or more 
this industrial area in the desert is first stop for many new 
troops arriving in saudi arabia the gritty landscape of dusty 
mills and corrogated metal buildings is covered with long rows of 
olive drab tents 
units arrive here each day to receive their assignments the 
expectation is they will quickly be shipped somewhere else 
welcome to ellis island one officer said by way of 
explanation 
the 265th quartermaster detachment a south carolina national 
guard unit mobilized to run water purification equipment in this 
dry country arrived over the weekend 
but so far the only water the 14 men have seen is in the 15 
liter bottles handed out to them several times a day like so many 
other units staying here the 265th is an orphan looking for a 
home 
we got to get going here said sgt ronnie jackson who 
leads the 14 men from allendale sc we need to go to a place we 
can start working 
the urgency to get out isnt rooted in work ethic alone as an 
intelligence officer pointed out matteroffactly this place is 
considered a prime iraqi target 
it doesnt take much to see that there are no bunkers no 
trenches no where to run or hide 
you get an air strike in here this place will get torn up 
bad said jackson 
so the sergeant spent his time looking to get the unit 
officially adopted driving to various headquarters areas trying 
to learn where his unit is headed 
the wide empty sixlane highways carried only a light traffic 
of us troops in humvees and pickups and saudis in toyotas and 
mercedes many of the saudis waved as they rocketed past at speeds 
well over 60 mph 
