<TEXT>
the beleaguered chairman of the national 
endowment for the arts is applauding a senate bill that would give 
the courts not his agency the burden of deciding whether some 
federally subsidized works of art are obscene 
nea chairman john e frohnmayer said the senate measure and a 
report by a bipartisan commission last week give us hope that the 
crisis will soon pass over federal support for controversial art 
frohnmayer refused however to scrap a muchcriticized 
requirement that nea grant recipients sign an antiobscenity pledge 
before they can receive federal money 
he said he would delay a decision on eliminating the pledge 
until congress decides whether to impose new antiobscenity 
restrictions on the endowment and a federal court in new york rules 
on the constitutionality of the pledge 
at a news conference monday at the national press club 
frohnmayer said there was zero truth to those rumors that he 
would resign soon after a turbulent year as nea chairman 
the endowment is an independent 171 million federal agency 
that supports a wide variety of artists and arts organizations it 
has been the target of heavy criticism for the past 18 months from 
conservative lawmakers and religious fundamentalists who accuse the 
nea of subsidizing obscene and sacrilegious works 
last week the senate labor and human resources approved a 
bipartisan compromise bill extending the nea for five years beyond 
sept 30 when its statutory authority expires the bill would 
require the nea to recoup funds from grant recipients who are 
convicted of violating obscenity laws 
frohnmayer said this provision puts the determination of 
obscenity in the courts where it should be 
last october at the urging of sen jesse helms rnc 
congress voted to prohibit the nea from spending federal funds on 
any works that may be considered obscene including depictions 
of homoeroticism sadomasochism and the sexual exploitation of 
children 
a month later frohnmayer began requiring grant recipients to 
sign a pledge that they would not use federal money to produce 
works that might be deemed obscene 
the antiobscenity pledge stirred widespread protests in the 
arts community a dozen grant recipients refused to sign it and 
forfeited their grants three federal lawsuits filed in new york 
and los angeles charge that the pledge violates first amendment 
guarantees of free expression 
the 12member independent study commission created by congress 
urged frohnmayer last week to scrap the pledge a similar plea was 
made earlier by the neas presidentially appointed advisory body 
the national council on the arts 
the study commission endorsed the nea but recommended changes in 
its grantmaking procedures to make the agency more responsive to 
the publics interests the panel also urged congress not to impose 
any new restrictions on the kinds of art eligible for nea subsidies 
when the current antiobscenity ban expires on sept 30 
