<TEXT>
federal researchers should be more openminded 
about unconventional treatments that show some potential to help 
cancer patients a fouryear congressional study concludes 
the study by the office of technology assessment found that none 
of the alternative methods it reviewed including psychological 
nutritional and herbal remedies was obviously or dramatically 
effective 
but the report also said these treatments have had little if 
any scientific review which leaves patients with no guidance if 
they want to supplement or replace their conventional treatment 
its very hard to get information beyond promotional 
brochures said roger c herdman who supervised the report 
which was released monday there isnt a lot in the peerreviewed 
literature where scientific findings are reported 
yet thousands of cancer patients have turned to alternative 
treatments most after undergoing at least some conventional 
treatment for their disease the report said 
its worthwhile to give serious thought to unconventional 
approaches to serious diseases herdman said 
we suggested a more systematic and more aggressive look be 
taken by some of the responsible agencies including the national 
cancer institute provided there was reason to believe the 
treatment could benefit patients he said 
the report urges researchers to take a sympathetic and 
thoughtful look at some of these treatments he said 
officials at the national cancer institute had not seen the 
report and therefore could not comment on it institute spokesman 
paul van nevel said 
the study was not intended to evaluate the effectiveness of 
alternative cancer treatments but rather to help members of 
congress deal with such issues as insurance reimbursement of cancer 
treatments and research and development funding rep john dingell 
dmich chairman of the house energy and commerce committee 
requested the review in august 1986 
dingell called the report balanced and said it tells us 
that some alternative approaches to cancer treatment can have both 
physiological and psychological benefits which should not be 
ignored by physicians 
it is clear we need better information on these treatments 
and that the federal government should consider its role in that 
effort he said 
proponents of unconventional treatments had been very critical 
of an earlier draft version of the report it was filled with 
errors and failed to fault the current system of evaluating these 
therapies they said 
however after hearing reports about the final version the 
criticism softened 
the report recommends that more information be gathered on the 
types of patients who use unconventional treatments it suggests 
the federal government could start a registry for documented 
reports of tumor regression that appears to be unrelated to 
conventional treatment the government also could collect 
information on documented adverse reactions the report said 
the report also urged federal funding of efforts to evaluate 
unconventional treatments 
some methods have been studied but overall these reviews 
generally have not been well designed and have not met with the 
approval of academic researchers the report said 
currently cancer treatments that are considered mainstream 
and are usually covered by medical insurance include surgery 
radiation therapy chemotherapy hormonal therapy and 
immunotherapy which involves manipulating a patients immune 
system to fight the cancer 
the report said that based on the little information available 
most of the patients who turn to an alternative treatment have had 
at least some conventional therapy many continue the mainstream 
approach while incorporating an alternative method the report 
said 
major clinics that offer unconventional therapies charge in the 
range of 5000 to 40000 for a course of treatment the report 
said 
among the alternatives reviewed the report found that 
welldesigned studies are beginning to look at the potential of 
psychological interventions like mental imagery and meditation it 
called the results so far encouraging but said the value of 
these approaches remain uncertain 
the report also reviews dietary treatments mixtures of herbal 
products and such biologic agents as laetrile which was popular in 
the 1970s and is currently offered by several clinics in mexico 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

