<TEXT>
ten years of boom times have suddenly gone 
bad along the dusty highway to iraq 
the unordered embargo on trade with turkeys neighbor has 
struck a devastating blow along the road to the border forcing 
hundreds of merchants to close their shops and seek jobs elsewhere 
local officials say 
the highway was all they had now of course they will go 
said neset okten mayor of silopi 
a string of small businesses including bakeries groceries and 
car repair shops are now empty forming an extended ghost town 
along the route 
silopi nine miles west of the iraqi border and neighboring 
cizre 18 miles farther west are on the only highway linking 
turkey with iraq 
in the past decade as turkish trade with iraq grew these 
oncesleepy towns of a few thousand population each enjoyed a boom 
and populations swelled to 30000 for silopi and 70000 for cizre 
about 5000 trucks and oil tankers passed through the towns 
daily local officials said last year turkey earned 480 million 
from transit fees 
the highway is two lanes in the border area but is also part of 
the e5 international highway that runs from western europe through 
turkey to the middle east 
most of the trucks carried goods for iraq food machinery 
even parts intended for an iraqi supergun that turkish officials 
managed to intercept moving in the other direction tankers 
carried crude oil from iraq to turkey 
the local people selling spare car parts food drinks and 
other goods to the drivers reaped profits from the heavy traffic 
now the road is empty save for some passenger buses and turkish 
military vehicles patrolling the border area for kurdush 
guerrillas 
merchants losses while devastating to local economies are 
believed to be only a fraction of the 4 billion turkey says it is 
losing this year because it closed two iraqi oil pipelines that run 
through the country and banned all trade with iraq 
bags of sugar spaghetti flour and spices were piled up against 
a wall at mehmet emins shop in cizres market place 
i havent sold anything today he said 
emin said he used to gross 110 a day before iraq invaded kuwait 
on aug 2 and set the persian gulf crisis in motion 
