<TEXT>
the turmoil in the persian gulf is hitting 
american consumers where it hurts in their wallets 
energy prices began soaring immediately after the iraqi invasion 
of kuwait on aug 2 crimping consumers power to purchase other 
items and threatening to topple the nation into a recession 
the government is scheduled today to release its first 
assessment of the inflationary damage at the retail level where it 
counts for consumers 
in advance most economists were predicting the labor 
departments consumer price index soared 08 percent in august 
double the 04 percent rise in july 
thats the equivalent of a 10 percent annual inflation rate and 
would be the steepest monthly increase since january when a cold 
snap sent fuel oil and vegetable prices skyrocketing and produced a 
11 percent overall price rise 
in a report last week the department said wholesale prices paid 
to producers such as factories and farmers jumped 13 percent the 
steepest rise in seven months 
georgia state university economist donald ratajczak who 
conducts his own inflation surveys was predicting about twothirds 
of the august consumer price rise would be attributed to energy he 
forecast a gasoline hike of 17 percent and a fuel oil rise of 26 
percent 
analysts are divided over how long the inflation jolt will last 
some are predicting the bad news will continue for months as the 
inflation works its way into chemicals plastics and other 
petroleumbased products 
by the end of 1990 the inflation rate for the year will 
register at around 6 percent ratajczak predicted up significantly 
from the 5 percent expected before the invasion and from the 46 
percent recorded in 1989 
others however believe the pain will be relatively 
shortlived they say economic growth is too weak to support an 
inflationary spiral 
the inflation climate will remain unpleasant for the next 
several months economist bruce steinberg of merrill lynch said 
in a recent newsletter but the economy is extremely weak 
possibly recessionary within a year the inflation rate is likely 
to be lower than it was just prior to the oil shock 
</TEXT>
