<TEXT>
oklahoma voters decide today whether to 
limit state lawmakers terms something no state ever has done 
the proposed constitutional amendment would put a 12year cap on 
service by members of the state house or senate 
supporters argued it would keep incumbents from becoming so 
entrenched they no longer worked for the people opponents 
contended passage would concentrate power in the hands of 
nonelected career bureaucrats and lobbyists 
oklahoma is the first state to bring such a proposal to the 
ballot said the national council of state legislators colorado 
and california will vote on similar proposals nov 6 similar 
legislation has been introduced in florida and new york 
there have been no limits on the terms of state or federal 
lawmakers since the constitution superseded the articles of 
confederation which had limited house terms to three years out of 
every six 
the oklahoma proposal got on the ballot through an initiative 
petition circulated by tulsa businessman lloyd noble ii he argued 
that legislators are so concerned about getting reelected they 
ignore important matters like waste in government 
all our legislators talk about cutting waste but they dont 
cut any waste that gets them elected noble said 
opponents said voters already can limit lawmakers terms by 
not reelecting them 
i just basically hate to see any deterioration of the right of 
the voters to decide his or her own representatives said senate 
president pro tem bob cullison 
other opponents noted that only 16 members of the 48member 
senate and 14 of the 101 house members had 12 or more years of 
service when the 1990 legislature adjourned 
legislators now in office would be allowed to serve 12 more 
years the ballot measure also provided that the constitutional 
provision would not go into effect until jan 1 
although legislators elected this year will take office in 
november noble said he believes the 12year limit would apply to 
them 
</TEXT>
