the weakening us economy ironically could 
help soften the expected balloon in the nations merchandise trade 
deficit brought on by the oilprice shock of the persian gulf 
crisis analysts say 
the price of oil has soared since the iraqi invasion of kuwait 
on aug 2 driving up americas energy bill the united states 
imports about 50 percent of its oil consumption 
but while oil prices are rising the us economy is slowing 
draining the amount of money consumers have to spend on cars made 
in japan and computers shipped from south korea the deficit is the 
difference between imports and exports thus trade deficit relief 
might be in the offing 
oil prices were rising even before the iraqi invasion however 
and analysts were looking for todays commerce department report on 
merchandise trade to see what effect it had on the july deficit 
many analysts thought it would top 7 billion the deficit 
totaled 507 billion in june the lowest since june 1983 when it 
fell to 396 billion 
higher july imported crude oil prices are likely to boost 
the oil deficit by about 500 million economists at mitsubishi 
bank wrote in their current weekly economic indicator report 
michael k evans head of evans economics inc a washington 
forecasting firm said oil prices rose between 2 and 3 in july to 
about 17 a barrel they had averaged 1464 a barrel in june 
meanwhile the us economy is slumping with growth in the 
first half of the year down to an annual rate of 12 percent from 
25 percent in 1989 and 45 percent in 1988 many analysts expect 
the business cycle to slide into a recession by the fourth quarter 
of this year if it is not already experiencing one 
and as the economy grows more sluggish consumers are growing 
more reluctant to spend not only on americanmade goods but on 
items imported from overseas as well 
if you look at imports of other commodities other than 
energy i would expect them to be fairly weak said economist 
cynthia latta of drimcgrawhill in lexington mass that should 
hold overall imports down 
for the first six months of 1990 the deficit averaged 764 
billion a month compared to 912 billion in 1989 
and before kuwait many analysts and government officials were 
predicting the deficit would total less than 100 billion this year 
for the first time since 1983 whether that goal can be attained 
now is questionable 
unless we have a recession that really is pretty nasty 
cropping up i wouldnt expect imports to fall sharply enough to 
allow us to get anywhere close to that number said robert 
brusca chief financial economist with nikko securities co 
international inc in new york 
at the same time the united states will see a slowdown in 
export growth because economic conditions are deteriorating 
overseas added lawrence chimerine senior fellow at the economic 
strategy institute a washington research organization 
