<TEXT>
the persian gulf crisis has cut short the 
economic boom of jordans only port and main tourist resort 
beaches normally packed with tourists are deserted aqabas 
wide treelined boulevards and oncecrowded shopping malls have 
become the haunt of stray cats searching vainly for scraps of food 
until iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait and the resulting turmoil 
in trade throughout the middle east aqaba was jordans fastest 
growing city and had a bright future 
but now tourism is dead the port is at a practical standstill 
and so is business in general bemoans bassam kakish president 
of the aqaba region development authority 
thewalls of kakishs office are lined with colored architects 
drawings of the tourism and other development projects along the 
sandy beaches and crystalclear waters of the red sea 
the port has been severely affected because 70 percent of its 
business was iraqi imports and exports and that trade has been 
killed by the unordered embargo on trade with iraq in 
retaliation for its seizure of kuwait 
aqaba with an estimated population of 45000 is near jordans 
southern tip sandwiched between saudi arabia and israel it sits 
next to the israeli resort city of eilat 
only two or three ships a day dock in the port compared with 
more than 20 before the crisis more than 7000 of the 11000 
jordanian trucks engaged in hauling goods to and from the port have 
been idled kakish said 
thousands of people have been flung out of work dockers in 
the port truck drivers and hundreds more providing auxiliary 
services this has brought business in town to a virtual 
standstill 
in the tourist sector kakish said aqaba catered to 150000 
european tourists last year and this year we expected even more we 
were actually 5000 beds short 
all the local hotels are expanding and new ones are under 
construction yet now all the hotels are empty and this is the 
beginning of the high season he said 
hoteliers confirmed that with the outbreak of the crisis guests 
began leaving fearing the region would be engulfed in a war 
the only guests we have now are the occasional journalists 
that come down from amman to visit the port and see how the 
sanctions are implemented said a receptionist at one of the main 
hotels who gave his name as mohammed 
weve had hundreds of cancellations and future bookings have 
dried up he said 
kakish estimates that aqaba will lose more than 12 billion 
from the combined collapse of its tourism and port business no end 
is in sight to the falloff which kakish believes is unfair since 
jordan is abiding by un sanctions against iraq 
people talk without reason of jordan as a war zone he said 
when will they regain confidence how long will this period of 
uncertainty continue one or two months one or two years 
