<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachevs unexpected call 
for a referendum on ending collectived farming indicates he is now 
having second thoughts about pushing ahead with a compromise plan 
to create a market economy gorbachevs proposal to put to the 
people whether to allow private ownership of land came monday as 
parliament opened debate on competing plans for salvaging the 
shortageplagued and grossly inefficient economy 
gorbachev speaking to parliament did not say when the 
referendum would be held who would vote or where he personally 
stood on the issue 
he is apparently reluctant either personally or politically to 
part with six decades of communist party ideological opposition to 
private ownership of land said professor murray feshbach of 
georgetown university in washington 
gorbachev just cant bring himself to turn in his party 
card feshbach said in a telephone interview 
soviet peasants were coerced into collectivization and all land 
became state property during a 19291932 campaign led by josef v 
stalin that is believed to have claimed the lives of between 5 
million and 10 million people 
the debate in the legislature monday turned tumultuous as 
delegates and economists rose to attack parts of all three economic 
reform proposals presented in the past week 
the compromise supported by gorbachev was criticized by 
supporters of both the other plans and the chances of a broad 
consensus appeared dim 
the most radical proposal known as the shatalin plan for its 
principal author economist stanislav shatalin would in 500 days 
give land back to farmers sell factories to private owners and 
move the soviet union toward a free market 
it would shift most economic authority from the central 
government to the increasingly separatist republics and deprive the 
national government of the right to levy taxes 
a more conservative proposal supported by prime minister 
nikolai ryzhkov would retain central control over the economy and 
move more slowly toward a heavily regulated market 
gorbachev on friday presented the compromise plan written by 
shatalin and another leading soviet economist abel aganbegyan it 
contains many elements of shatalins radical 500day plan but would 
move at a slower pace and not disturb the central governments 
power to levy taxes 
the compromise proposal also backs away from private ownership 
of land while shatalins 500day plan calls for selling some land 
to individuals for nominal prices the compromise calls for leasing 
it 
gorbachev has urged a compromise to avoid a split with the 
parliament of the russian federation the largest of the 15 soviet 
republics with half the countrys people and threequarters of its 
land 
the russian parliament overwhelmingly adopted shatalins 500day 
plan last week 
thousands of people marched through moscow on sunday to demand 
the resignation of gorbachev ryzhkov and the council of ministers 
for failing to solve the countrys economic problems 
gorbachev rejected the calls monday saying reshuffling the 
top echelons of power would draw us into grim political 
battles and would heighten confrontation in society at a time 
when we most badly need consolidation to carry out the market 
economy program 
