prime minister nikolai i ryzhkov indicated today 
he will resign or refuse to cooperate if the national legislature 
adopts radical economic reforms that he opposes 
ryzhkovs comments came during a break in the supreme soviet 
legislatures second day of debate over three competing economic 
reform plans the most conservative of which ryzhkov put forward 
last week 
as prime minister ryzhkov 61 oversees the government 
bureaucracy and could play a key role in putting any reform plan 
into effect or obstructing it 
asked by a reporter whether he would step down if the 
legislature rejected his plan ryzhkov said i will carry out 
that in which i believe thats all i will not carry out any other 
plan 
ryzhkov also said last week that if his plan was defeated he 
would take responsibility for it before the people and the 
supreme soviet but he has avoided making a clear promise to step 
aside if radical reforms are enacted 
several leading reformers including moscow mayor gavriil popov 
have demanded ryzhkovs resignation since he presented his plan 
which envisions continued central control of the economy while slow 
moves are made toward a marketbased system 
by contrast the radical reform plan adopted a week ago by the 
parliament of russia the largest soviet republic calls for 
switching to a market within just 500 days it would retur land to 
private farmers sell government enterprises to private 
stockholders and gradually remove statecontrolled prices on many 
goods 
thousands of people marched through moscow on sunday to demand 
that ryzhkov resign for failing to improve the soviet economy 
plagued by shortages of consumer goods ranging from tobacco to 
paper and shoes 
but president mikhail s gorbachev rejected those demands 
monday telling parliament that reshuffling the top echelons of 
power would draw us into grim political battles and would 
heighten confrontation in society at a time when we most badly need 
consolidation to carry out the market economy program 
instead gorbachev proposed a national referendum on ending 
collectivized farming he did not say when the referendum would be 
held who would vote or where he personally stood on the issue 
soviet peasants were coerced into joining collective farms and 
all land became state property during a 19291932 campaign led by 
josef stalin that is believed to have claimed the lives of between 
5 million and 10 million people 
gorbachev has backed a compromise economic plan that contains 
many elements of the radical 500day plan but would move at a 
slower pace and not disturb the central governments power to levy 
taxes 
the compromise proposal also backs away from private ownership 
of land while economist stanislav shatalins 500day plan calls 
for selling some land to individuals for nominal prices the 
compromise calls for leasing it 
gorbachev apparently is reluctant either personally or 
politically to part with six decades of communist party 
ideological opposition to private ownership of land said professor 
murray feshbach of georgetown university in washington 
gorbachev just cant bring himself to turn in his party 
card feshbach said in a telephone interview 
gorbachev has urged a compromise to avoid a split with the 
parliament of the russian federation the largest of the 15 soviet 
republics with half the countrys people and threequarters of its 
land the russian parliament overwhelmingly adopted shatalins 
500day plan last week 
