<TEXT>
blood and saliva taken from a former dallas 
minister suspected in the near strangulation of his wife will be 
used for dna profiling a newspaper reported today 
federal and local authorities hope the scientific process will 
help identify the attacker of margaret railey who has been 
comatose since the attack in april 1987 the dallas times herald 
reported 
walker railey formerly a prominent methodist minister has been 
the only suspect while maintaining his innocence he has declined 
to testify before a grand jury and a judge found him responsible 
in a civil proceeding 
fbi agents in california on friday took railey to a detention 
center where he gave courtordered blood and saliva samples 
fbi and dallas police wouldnt comment officially but sources 
within both agencies told the newspaper they were taking the body 
fluids for dna testing 
dna deoxyribonucleic acid is found in every cell and is 
unique in each person its use as an identification tool is 
considered the most important development in criminal 
investigations since fingerprinting body tissue such as hair 
skin or blood is often found at crime scenes 
the railey attack happened before dna testing was available but 
the technique can still be applied because there is a long shelf 
life of the physical evidence the newspaper quoted an 
unidentified fbi agent as saying 
norman kinne the chief assistant dallas district attorney said 
dna profiling of railey was the fbis idea he added that if the 
testing links railey to the crime scene it certainly would be 
significant to the case 
the fbi has been investigating the attack because of raileys 
claims he received threatening letters before his wife was 
attacked police later concluded that they had been typed at 
raileys own church 
mrs railey was attacked in the garage of the couples home 
while railey claimed to have been at a library it was later 
determined he also had been at the home of his mistress a dallas 
psychologist with whom he later lived in california 
at the time of the attack railey was pastor at the 6000member 
first united methodist church of dallas subsequently he left the 
ministry gave guardianship of his two children over to friends 
and moved to california 
railey was held responsible for his wifes attack in a civil 
trial and was ordered to pay 18 million he has since filed for 
divorce from mrs railey who remains in a vegetative state in a 
nursing home 
