<TEXT>
pilots over age 60 have twice as many 
accidents as those in their 50s but theyre still safer than 
pilots in their 20s or 30s according to a congressional report 
the office of technology assessment reached no conclusion on 
whether the federal aviation administration should revise its 
regulation forcing retirement at age 60 for pilots on major 
airlines those which operate planes with more than 30 seats 
there is no such requirement for corporate private or 
commuterairline pilots 
critics have argued the age60 rule for airlines arbitrarily 
grounds many healthy experienced pilots and denies the traveling 
public the benefit of their skill 
they have called for more flexible rules tied to stringent 
medical examinations but the ota questioned whether current 
testing techniques could adequately detect the subtle mental 
deterioration which it deems the principal hazard posed by aging 
pilots 
the otas study based on average accidents per 100000 flight 
hours for all pilots with more than 1000 hours of flight 
experience found that pilots between ages 60 to 69 have an 
accident rate that is 21 times higher than the accident rate for 
50 to 59yearolds 
however the same data show that the accident rate for the 
60to 69yearold pilots is less than that for pilots in the 
3039yearold and 2029yearold age groups the report said 
it found that experience clearly counts noting that pilots over 
60 with more than 5000 flight hours have a lower accident rate 
than pilots of any age with 1000 to 5000 flight hours but in all 
experience groups the accident rate goes up after 60 the ota 
said 
the congressional agency said the safety issue for major 
airlines has little to do with the vulnerability of aging pilots to 
sudden impairment a heart attack say since a copilot and 
sometimes a third flight officer are on the flight deck and could 
take the controls in such cases 
rather piloterror accidents are almost always based on 
mental error rather than the pilots incapacitation and the data 
showing higher accident rates for the over60 bracket suggest 
that the increase may be due to subtle agerelated 
deterioration in cognitive function 
thus more stringent or frequent medical exams likely would have 
little effect on accident rates unless they involved more accurate 
neuropsychological measurements than currently available the ota 
said 
the airline industry and the air line pilots association both 
support the age60 mandatory retirement rule 
</TEXT>
