<TEXT>
the us merchandise trade deficit soared 75 
percent in july for its steepest increase in eight years the 
government said renewing recessionary fears even before the 
effects of the persian gulf crisis are felt 
the commerce department said the deficit totaled 933 billion 
up sharply from 534 billion in june and the worst imbalance since 
last januarys 102 billion the surge was the largest since the 
shortfall jumped 205 percent to 55 billion in august 1982 a 
spokesman said 
commerce secretary robert a mosbacher noted the july report 
contained the last trade data unaffected by the disruptions caused 
by the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait 
the rise in oil prices since then is likely to increase the 
average trade deficit for the last five months by an amount in 
excess of 2 billion per month mosbacher said 
in addition to the effects of the oilprice shock many private 
analysts pointed to a 64 percent decline in exports in july and 
questioned whether much improvement was in the offing 
over the past three years fully onethird of overall us 
economic growth has been supplied by surging export sales that had 
become even more important recently as consumer spending faded in 
the face of adverse economic news 
but mark m zandi an economist with regional financial 
associates in west chester pa said high interest rates and 
slower economic growth overseas are going to take a bite out of 
our export picture he said 
david jones an economist with aubrey g lanston amp co a new 
york securities dealer added that while its unlikely the trade 
numbers will continue to look as bad as they did in july they do 
give us a hint that we have come to the end of major improvements 
in trade 
in fact the united states had a deficit of 133 billion with 
western europe because of falling exports after posting a surplus 
of 806 million in june 
exports have been the only area of strength in the economy for 
several years now said bruce steinberg senior economist for 
merrill lynch in new york if they fall theres no area of 
strength and thats very bothersome 
exports which posted a record 343 billion in june fell to 
320 billion in july imports jumped 45 percent to 414 billion 
the deficit is the difference between the two 
nevertheless mosbacher said exports were up 81 percent during 
the first seven months of the year while imports rose just 33 
percent meaning the 1990 deficit was running at an annual rate of 
950 billion the deficit last year totaled 10940 billion 
he remained optimistic that the nonoil deficit which he 
called a better indicator of international competitiveness 
would decline further from the current 458 billion rate 
oil imports in july rose 79 prcent to 398 billion but that 
was due to increased volume rather than prices americans imported 
885 million barrels a day up from 840 million in june while the 
average price per barrel edged down from 1464 to 1450 
since the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait however crude oil 
prices have surpassed 33 a barrel 
exports slipped in part because of a 500 million drop in 
aircraft shipments but decreases also were posted in all major 
categories capital goods foods automobiles industrial supplies 
and consumer goods 
at the same time consumer and capital goods automobiles and 
industrial supplies added to the import total 
as usual the biggest deficit was with japan a 297 billion 
imbalance down from a 307 billion deficit in june 
other deficits included taiwan 114 billion china 113 
billion canada 992 million brazil 335 million korea 623 
million and hong kong 439 million 
