<TEXT>
the seabrook nuclear power plant has been 
allowed to go into full operation within three miles of a popular 
beach without adequate plans for evacuation in the event of 
disaster the us court of appeals was told tuesday 
as opponents of the plant demonstrated outside the court heard 
arguments on the petition of massachusetts officials and 
environmental groups to revoke the license issued for the new 
hampshire facility 
the plant was licensed by the commission in march after nearly 
two decades of court challenges and thousands of arrests in mass 
demonstrations it began operations last month 
lawyers for the nuclear regulatory commission and the new 
hampshire public service company principal owner of the plant 
defended the licensing saying the nrc followed longestablished 
principles that provided substantial protection they said there 
was no way to know in advance just how much protection would be 
adequate 
the idea is to create a plan that provides some measure of 
protection to the people said john f cordes jr attorney for 
the nrc he said the procedures were not designed to permit the 
commission to revisit a site decision once it was made 
judge stephen f williams a member of the threejudge panel 
that heard the arguments asked if this meant that you do the 
best you can in the circumstances if that means distributing bibles 
and suicide pills 
cordes replied that the commissions rules would allow it to 
change its procedures if it were faced with a site where it 
believed no one could be evacuated and there was no shelter 
that is not remotely the case at seabrook he said 
robert a backus representing two citizens groups opposed to 
the plant said the nearby beach attracts at least 50000 people on 
fine summer days he said the only shelters available are motels 
cottages and structures such as ice cream parlors with screened 
porches 
although there is one interstate highway in the area most of 
the potential escape routes are twolane roads he said he said 
traffic jams in the area sometimes last for as long as seven hours 
he said the commission failed to follow its procedures in 
approving an evacuation plan for people living in 17 new hampshire 
communities and six in neighboring massachusetts 
the commission did not make a judgment on whether or not there 
were adequate evacuation plans backus told the court 
they basically made a judgment without looking at the 
evidence said john traficante assistant massachusetts attorney 
general we are not saying they drew the wrong line we are 
saying they drew no line 
traficante argued that the commission relied on a check list 
that doesnt have any teeth on this basis he said it could 
approve a site on 42nd and broadway in new york 
cordes said the commissions procedures assured that there would 
be a full measure of planning for an emergency and that this 
would be substantial protection for the public 
this is not a secret approach he said its nothing 
mysterious 
thomas g dignan jr representing the owners argued the 
adequacy of an evacuation plan is something that will never be 
determined at a nuclear site until the day of the accident 
he said it would depend on such things as the nature of the 
accident and the wind direction at the time 
