the united states is on the verge 
of paying a 200 million claim brought by iran western diplomats 
said tuesday the payment would pave the way for the resolution of 
a decadeold dispute 
the diplomats speaking on condition of anonymity said 
settlement of the claim stemming from iranian payments made on 
undelivered us weaponry was imminent 
the case is part of the foreign military sales claim being 
arbitrated here by the iranunited states claims tribunal the 
9yearold tribunal is charged with arbitrating all commercial and 
governmenttogovernment claims between the two nations arising 
from the 1979 iranian revolution and the ensuing expropriations and 
broken contracts 
iran has set the total military sales claim involving 1200 
cases in all at 11 billion a figure the us government says is 
inflated 
once the case involving the undelivered weaponry is settled the 
200 million will be deposited in the socalled security account 
from which money is paid out to claimants at the tribunal the 
money is now in a trust fund 
another case close to being settled involves weapons that iran 
had sent to the united states for repairs but never got back the 
weapons were impounded by the us government after the 1979 
seizing of the us embassy in tehran by islamic militants 
the sources would not give a time frame for settlement of this 
case nor put a dollar amount on it but the settlement is believed 
to amount to up to 300 million 
the agreement is were paying them an agreedupon value for 
the equipment and we get to keep it said a western diplomat 
the military equipment impounded by the us government includes 
several airplanes airplane engines and even a world war iiera 
dieselpowered submarine now in the philadelphia navy yard 
at the time of the revolution iran had large numbers of 
warplanes and several destroyers on order in the united states but 
those were canceled by mutual agreement in light of the freeze on 
military transfers 
the largest foreign military sales claim is irans 5 billion 
demand for damages resulting from the us governments refusal to 
license exports of weaponry and other military material tehran had 
ordered the iranian government has never explained precisely how 
it arrived at that figure 
but tehran has on several occasions said that return of its 
assets held by the united states was a precondition for its 
intervention on behalf of western hostages held in lebanon the 
captors of the 13 known western hostages are believed to be 
proiranian shiite moslem militants 
