tropical storm marie headed farther south of the 
hawaiian islands than previously expected tuesday but forecasters 
cautioned residents to prepare for effects of the storm 
high surf kicked up by the storm hammered the eastern and 
southern shores of hawaii island prompting the closing of punaluu 
beach park surf there ranged from 8 to 10 feet up from a normal 
average of 1 to 2 feet hawaii county civil defense administrator 
harry kim said 
the southeastern section of the island also experienced some 
strong gusty wind that blew debris onto some roads kim said 
there were no reports of any property damage caused by the surf 
or wind he said 
the storm was expected to pass about 250 miles south of the 
south point area of hawaii island 
on monday the national weather service predicted the storm 
would come within 130 miles of hawaii island the big island but 
the storm began veering from a westerly course to the southwest 
at 2 am the storm was about 235 miles south southeast of 
hilo on hawaii islands east coast and was moving to the 
southwest at 9 mph 
the storm downgraded from a hurricane sunday had a maximum 
sustained wind speed of 65 mph with 85 mph gusts gale force wind 
extended 125 miles out from the center 
the storms intensity was expected to change little until the 
same time wednesday the weather service said 
a tropical storm warning remained in effect for hawaii island 
and a tropical storm watch was in effect for the islands of maui 
molokai and lanai no storm warnings were issued for kauai and oahu 
islands honolulu is located on oahu 
a tropical storm warning means wind blowing at a sustained speed 
of 39 mph to 73 mph is possible within 24 hours or less a watch 
means there is a threat of tropical storm conditions within 36 
hours 
