<TEXT>
methadone programs could be more effective in 
helping stop the spread of aids if patients were given doses large 
enough to wean them from their heroin habit addiction treatment 
experts told lawmakers tuesday 
experts also testified that needleexchange and outreach 
programs are effective ways to reduce behavior that puts 
intravenous drug users at high risk of becoming infected with the 
aids virus 
however more than 80 percent of the estimated 15 million iv 
drug users are not being reached with treatment programs they 
said 
rep ted weiss dny and chairman of the house government 
operations subcommittee on human resources estimated that more 
than 2 million people iv drug users and their sexual partners 
are at high risk of getting aids because they share needles and 
have sex without protective condoms 
these users and their partners have fallen through the 
cracks he said their addiction is not being treated and they 
are not being protected from hiv infection 
according to a report by the congressional office of technology 
assessment released at the hearing methadone programs differ 
widely including doses of the synthetic narcotic given to wean 
heroin users from their addiction 
an average daily dosage of 80 milligrams of methadone is 
considered sufficient to wean most users from their heroin habit 
the lowest effective dose is believed to be around 60 milligrams 
the report said 
however a recent survey of 24 methadone programs found the 
average daily dosages ranged from 21 to 67 milligrams the report 
said twentyone of them gave an average daily dose of less than 60 
milligrams 
the reluctance to use higher dosages of methadone is rooted in 
the belief that the narcoticfree state is optimal and that 
methadone is a medicallysupervised narcotic addiction said 
diana hartel an assistant professor at albert einstein college of 
medicine in new york 
most addicts on lowdose methadone treatment will relapse into 
drug use repeatedly putting them at high risk for aids again she 
said 
the human immunodeficiency virus called hiv is spreading rapidly 
among intravenousdrug users who often share the needles they use 
to inject drugs they in turn transmit the infection to their 
sexual partners and the women transmit it to their babies 
methadone is not a treatment for cocaine and other nonopiate 
drug abuse nor is it effective for all heroin users 
but the ota report concludes that even if treatment for drug 
abuse is not 100 percent effective it may markedly decrease drug 
use for extended periods and therefore decrease the probability of 
hiv transmission 
it should be emphasized that when these interventions are 
applied on a very large scale to hundreds of thousands of people 
the public health impact of an intervention with even limited 
effectiveness can be substantial 
the report also said the need to prevent the further spread of 
aids increases the pressure for reexamination and scientific 
evaluation of public policies with regard to the availability of 
syringes and needles 
holly hagan an epidemiologist at the tacomapierce county 
health department told the lawmakers that since the tacoma wash 
needleexchange program began in august 1988 the number of drug 
users in the area has not increased as some critics feared 
also the program has led iv drug users to cut down their use of 
shared needles and to increase their use of bleach to sterilize 
syringes she said 
