<TEXT>
nasa engineers baffled by 
columbias persistent fuel leaks pored over data tuesday from the 
shuttles fourth failed launch attempt and pushed ahead for next 
months flight of discovery 
columbias commander vance brand said before leaving for johnson 
space center in houston that he and his sixman crew were 
disappointed the shuttle did not lift off early tuesday as planned 
the next launch attempt for the astronomy mission will be no 
earlier than november 
most of us have been involved in the space flight business for 
some time and we know from experience that hardware problems can 
be difficult and it does not pay to fly until the spacecraft is 
ready brand said 
the astronomy mission is very worthwhile and the crew is 
ready and anxious to fly as soon as the remaining hydrogen leaks 
are repaired 
nasas fourth attempt to launch columbia with a 150 million 
astronomical observatory ended abruptly monday evening about seven 
hours before planned liftoff despite repairs hydrogen flooded the 
engine compartment as the shuttle was being fueled 
it was the third time since may that columbias countdown was 
halted because of leaking hydrogen 
were really at a loss on this particular problem said 
david winterhalter director of systems engineering and analysis 
for the national aeronautics and space administration 
engineers are a resourceful group were digging in thinking 
more about it what is it we can do we havent done 
nasa was forming an investigative team tuesday to look into the 
matter 
henry pohl director of engineering at johnson space center 
said hydrogen appears to be escaping from a pinsize hole or 
several tinier cracks inside columbias crowded engine compartment 
he said the leaks are difficult to trace because they appear only 
when the liquid hydrogen is at its coldest minus 423 degrees 
fahrenheit 
officials believe the leaks are linked to the dismantling of 
columbia after its last flight in january workers took apart the 
engine compartment in a search for contamination by a 
metalpolishing abrasive 
i think we created a problem in that process pohl said 
someplace we didnt get a seal back on right or something 
insulation probably will have to be removed in the engine 
compartment a timeconsuming job pohl said workers are not 
expected to gain access to the area until wednesday 
pohl said hes not worried discovery might have hydrogen leaks 
similar to those plaguing columbia and atlantis 
discovery is scheduled to lift off around oct 8 with a 
plutoniumpowered satellite that will explore the suns poles 
if discovery does not lift off with the ulysses satellite by 
oct 23 the 750 million mission will have to wait until late 1991 
when earth the sun and jupiter are back in the proper alignment 
nasa has not decided whether to conduct a tanking test on 
discovery before launch because it takes about five days 
discovery experienced no problems during its flight in april 
with the hubble space telescope which later was found to have a 
flawed mirror that was the last time a shuttle has flown 
john pike director of the federation of american scientists 
space policy project said the fact nasa has launched shuttles 35 
times proves they can make it work in general 
the problem is making it work in particular right now pike 
said the bottom line is its more bad news when they really 
could use some good news 
