<DOCNO> AP900918-0125 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
computer ignorance at the agriculture 
department cost the public nearly 62 million when 7 million might 
have been sufficient to cover the job according to testimony 
tuesday before congress 
at issue is a project started in 1983 when the agriculture 
stabilization and conservation service contracted with the arthur 
andersen accounting firm to design two nationwide computer systems 
to monitor commodities inventories 
the firm wouldnt take the job unless the 7 million contract 
included a cost plus clause or one that provides an openended 
contract in case unforeseen expenses arise the firm said it needed 
that guarantee because of the vagueness of the services request 
most agencies by now have learned that cost plus is a ticket 
for automatic disaster said rep robert wise dwva whose 
house government operations subcommittee on agriculture is 
investigating the contract 
basically andersens job was to design a system for users who 
didnt know exactly what they wanted said jayetta hecker a 
director at the general accounting office which conducted a review 
of the computer system for wise 
she said andersen was not always required to correct defects at 
its own expense but did nothing illegal under the contract 
it was ineffective management and oversight along with 
poorly defined needs and inconsistent direction at the top levels 
of the agriculture service that caused costs to escalate she said 
in the last seven years six people have served as the deputy 
administrator for management hecker said this lack of 
continuity has contributed to decisions to start stop and restart 
the project which has resulted in additional costs 
rep glenn english dokla pointed out that administrators 
job at the stabilization and conservation service has been filled 
by political appointees whose credentials have not always included 
computer expertise 
basically weve had political hacks holding the job he 
said 
they didnt know enough about what they wanted and where they 
were going did they he asked hecker they were sheep to be 
shorn 
thats a pretty good characterization she said 
dr sarita schotta a computer expert who has been deputy 
administrator of the service for the last year tried to assure the 
congressional subcommittee that she was providing the kind of 
supervision the project should have had all along 
she said the computer system should be complete by next year 
she emphasized that the technological advances involved 3000 field 
offices 
part of the oversight problem came because the agency was so 
overwhelmed with getting software out in 300 counties she said 
the folks they were training already had 20 to 30 years in county 
office the last they thought theyd be doing was using 
computers 
the stabilization and conservation service is in charge of 
administering farm commodity conservation and emergency assistance 
programs including commodity loans and price support payments to 
farmers it handles billions of dollars each year 
in 1989 for example its program and administrative costs 
amounted to 13 billion by the end of the fiscal year its 
commodities inventories totaled nearly 4 billion 
its automated system for tracking acquisition storage 
movement sale and donation of grain and processed commodities had 
not been updated since the 1950s 
