<TEXT>
polar explorer will steger entertained members 
of congress tuesday with tales of his dogsled trek across 
antarctica but his support for legislation to make the frozen 
continent a world park met with a cold response 
steger of ely minn was the star witness when the house 
interior subcommittee opened hearings on legislation sponsored by 
rep bruce vento dminn that would ban us mineral exploration 
and curtail other development damaging antarcticas environment 
internationally weve been dragging our feet when it comes to 
the antarctic issue steger told the panel theres an 
opportunity to take a leadership role for the environment 
steger coled a sixmember international transantarctica 
expedition which completed the longest unmechanized passage across 
the continent in march 
he described the teams battle with a 2monthlong storm when 
winds hit 35 to 50 mph and their fears that they wouldnt find a 
companion who became lost overnight shortly before the end of the 
3741mile trek 
its almost like crossing another planet steger said 
the united states should take the lead to ensure the continent 
stays as pristine as it is now even though it may contain valuable 
deposits of uranium and platinum he said 
in order to preserve this place it may be best that we leave 
it said rep jim oberstar dminn 
but officials with the departments of state and interior said 
other nations with interests in antarctica must cooperate before 
the united states could agree to banning mining and turning 
antarctica into a nature reserve 
however unlikely it may seem now it is possible to envision 
circumstances where shortages of critical mineral resources may 
force other nations to ignore a ban said william houston a 
deputy assistant secretary of interior 
negotiating an effective agreement to protect the antarctic 
environment under these circumstances would be very difficult 
the existing convention on the regulation of antarctic mineral 
resource activities prohibits mineral exploration on the continent 
unless there is a consensus that it would not hurt the environment 
houston said 
vento argued that cramra signed in 1988 was a step in the 
wrong direction in that it provided the basis for future mining 
the united states instead should take the initiative in prohibiting 
antarctic mineral development he said 
peter wilkins director of polar programs for the national 
science foundation said the antarctic legislation could disrupt 
scientific research in the region at a time when nsf is remedying 
past environmental problems 
the legislation would apply all us environmental and historic 
preservation laws to the continent without regard to its unique 
situation he said 
for example us law could require chemical processing of waste 
water and cause more damage than current treatment methods 
recommended by scientists wilkins said 
