<TEXT>
federal safety officials proposed a 12 
million fine tuesday against a texas metal company accused of 
failing to report workplace injuries such as amputations cuts 
fractures and eye injuries 
the occupational safety and health administration cited kaspar 
wire works inc of shiner texas for knowingly and repeatedly 
violating federal laws governing the record keeping and reporting 
of workplace injuries and illnesses 
kaspar spokesman dan price said company officials would not 
comment until they could review the allegations 
the company was cited for 385 instances of alleged willful 
failure to record or accurately record injuries and illnesses in 
1988 and 1989 osha said 
other alleged violations included failure to provide medical 
records in a timely fashion and not reporting injuries to 
employees 
in addition there were several serious violations of osha 
standards governing handrails on stairs air compressor alarms 
containers for hazardous liquids electrical grounding and labeling 
containers of hazardous chemicals 
willful violations are those committed with an intentional 
disregard of or plain indifference to federal job safety laws 
a serious violation is one in which there is a substantial 
probability that death or serious physical harm could result and 
the employer knew or should have known of the hazard 
kaspar located about 90 miles south of austin employs about 
850 workers it makes newspaper vending machines and other metal 
products including wire baskets and barbecue grills 
kaspar has 15 working days to contest the allegations before an 
independent review commission 
