<TEXT>
the second summer cleanup of beaches 
tarred with crude oil spilled from the exxon valdez ended with 
state officials still worried that buried blobs of oil could cause 
more environmental damage 
exxon crews scoured contaminated shorelines for five months 
starting in april to remove oil left through the winter after the 
987foot tanker slammed onto a reef in march 1989 and spilled 
nearly 11 million gallons into prince william sound 
most beaches still covered with oil after the agitation of 
typically violent winter storms were cleaned up but many large 
collections of crude oil lie offshore covered by shifting sand and 
gravel 
the same forces that buried it can unbury it state 
spokesman ernie piper said 
gov steve cowper said hes worried that oil untouched by the 
cleanup will leach toxic substances for a long long time 
initially 1245 miles were coated with spilled oil piper said 
at the start of the 1990 cleanup about 100 miles of beach remained 
tainted he said 
by saturday when exxon shut down operations for the winter 
only four miles were classified as heavily oiled piper said 
cowper commended exxon and the coast guard for what was 
accomplished but fretted about the environmental future of the 
area where thousands of animals live and breed 
i dont think well ever see the point where the spiller and 
the regulator will ever agree to everything cowper said last 
week its our job to bark at the heels of everyone its our 
beach 
there is no agreement about how to best deal with buried oil 
some say it should be dug up others say environmental disruption 
caused by digging would be worse than leaving the oil untouched 
otto harrison exxons general manager in alaska said cleanup 
work and winter wave action produced a rapid recovery of prince 
william sound and the gulf of alaska 
the oil company pointed to a record 1990 salmon catch as partial 
proof fishermen hauled in 43 million pink salmon nearly 50 
percent more than the record set in 1987 the salmon have a 
twoyear life cycle meaning the ones caught this year were those 
that swam out to sea in 1989 during the height of the spill 
inspectors said this years catch was high quality 
coast guard rear adm david ciancaglini said he was happy with 
the second summer cleanup and discounted the flurry of state 
complaints accompanying its close 
the controversy is over as far as im concerned he said 
lets get out of here on a happy note and do whatever we have to 
do to finish up next year 
exxon said it would resume the cleanup in 1991 if the coast 
guard decides it is needed the state plans to draw up its own list 
of areas to be cleaned the oil company said it spent 2 billion on 
the cleanup in 1989 and 200 million more this year 
