butte county supervisors narrowly 
averted the nations first county bankruptcy tuesday by approving 
an 111 million bailout offered by gov george deukmejian 
the board voted 32 to accept the republican governors 
proposal which local officials said will avert immediate 
bankruptcy but wont stave off the possibility of bankruptcy next 
year 
were only putting off the inevitable said supervisor hack 
mcinturf 
county officials blamed the expense of programs required by the 
state 
under the agreement deukmejian proposed deferring payment of 
more than 63 million owed the state for fire protection services 
postponed the states demand for payment of a 2 million matching 
share for a new butte county jail and offered a 115 million 
direct cash grant 
the proposal also calls for the county to raise some 165 
million by boosting local fees including property tax collections 
and jail booking fees the payment deferrals will allow the county 
to use those funds for local programs and services 
in return the county agreed to scale back requests for new law 
enforcement services increases in pay for county workers and other 
programs the county said earlier it needed 141 million to keep 
from going bankrupt a figure that included expanded jail 
facilities and more deputies 
the agreement followed weeks of acrimonious negotiations between 
the state and the county which is last among californias 58 
counties in the amount of money it spends per capita on government 
services and last in the proportion of sheriffs deputies to 
population 
the county in northern califrnia is largely rural with an 
economy based on ranching and farming and has less than 200000 
people oroville the county seat is 66 miles north of sacramento 
the crisis arose after county officials were unable to balance 
this years 155 million budget 
they complained that fully 85 percent of their money was locked 
into existing programs by state statute such as welfare and 
health care for the poor and fire protection services 
board chairman ed mclaughlin along with the county supervisors 
association of california said that since the state didnt fully 
reimburse the county for the mandated services the county was 
forced to cut local services in order to finance the states 
demands 
mclaughlin voted against accepting the agreement saying the 
county had earlier pledged to declare bankruptcy unless the state 
offered the full 141 million 
