the senate endorsed a measure tuesday that 
would allow states to close their borders to other states garbage 
to protect shrinking landfill capacity 
sen dan coats rind said the proposal would give every 
state the right to determine its own destiny in managing trash 
through bans or higher fees for outofstate waste 
i wanted a fair shot at this the freshman senator said 
after prevailing over the objections of new jersey democratic 
senators bill bradley and frank lautenberg on a 6831 vote im 
content with it 
under coats proposal offered as an amendment to the district 
of columbia appropriations bill states could block garbage imports 
as long as they had a 20year solid waste plan in place 
bradley and lautenberg concerned their state would be overrun 
by trash if the measure were to become law promised to continue 
fighting when the appropriations bill reaches a housesenate 
conference committee 
the dc appropriations bill is also in danger of a presidential 
veto because it contains abortion funding language that led to two 
vetoes last year 
coats promised a tough fight to keep his measure alive 
if its knocked out well be back next year at minimum we 
have established a 2to1 majority to do something about this 
problem 
lautenberg has accused coats of playing electionyear politics 
with the garbage issue we knew we were on the lesspopular side 
of the issue he said 
new jersey is the largest exporter of solid waste to indiana 
landfills which are eight to 10 years from reaching their 
capacity coats said 
the amendment would give any state the power to impose 
unlimited punitive fees on outofstate garbage said 
lautenberg who said bans could be imposed suddenly and without 
environmental protection agency review a state writes its own 
ticket 
bradley and lautenberg charged the coats measure would block 
development of a comprehensive national solid waste policy by 
pitting state against state they said it also would undermine 
recycling new jersey has set a 60 percent recycling goal by 1995 
