<DOCNO> AP900918-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the house judiciary committee on tuesday 
approved a plan under which makers of computer softwear could bar 
video stores and others from renting them to customers 
manufacturers have complained that the rentals of video games 
are cutting into sales 
the bill sponsored by rep mike synar dokla is similar to a 
law already passed by congress under which record manufacturers are 
allowed to bar rentals 
the measure sailed through judiciary committee on a voice vote 
despite objections from video rental store operators 
sponsors are expected to push for early action on the measure 
with congress expected to leave washington for the campaign trail 
in a matter of weeks the senate already has passed similar 
legislation 
the idea behind the bill is that it is easy to copy both records 
and computer softwear stored on floppy discs the rentals are 
therefore considered to undercut the copyrights held by the 
manufacturers 
games often cost between 40 and 50 
under the bill manufacturers would have the option of allowing 
rentals or barring them 
in the case of records most makers do not allow rentals 
actually the bill applies to a wide range of computer softwear 
in addition to video games but the rental of games by stores that 
specialize mainly in renting movies is the main focus of the issue 
the japanese manufacturer nintendo asked to have its games 
included in the bill but the committee balked at that lawmakers 
said nintendo games are not readily copied and therefore the 
companys copyrights are not endangered by rentals 
the bill specifies that the measure not only does not apply to 
nintendo but also softwear embodied in machines such as cars and 
microwaves 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

