<TEXT>
the united states soviet union britain 
france and china have agreed on the basic guidelines for an air 
embargo on iraq to cut it off from the rest of the world a top 
soviet official said tuesday 
those nations which are the five permanent security council 
members are now refining the language of a council resolution so 
it conforms to international air traffic laws said soviet deputy 
foreign minister yuli vorontsov 
we dont want anyone to be hurt he said and then added 
we just want to hurt iraq just a little 
un diplomats and officials from the permanent five met tuesday 
to continue refining the text of the resolution 
defense ministers from nine west european nations agreed tuesday 
at a meeting in paris to coordinate their air and ground forces in 
the gulf and enforce the un air embargo when it takes effect 
vorontsov and other diplomats said the full 15member security 
council is expected to pass the resolution within days before 
french president francois mitterrand arrives to deliver a speech 
condemning iraq on monday before the general assembly 
mitterrand was outraged by iraqi raids last friday on the 
french belgian dutch and canadian missions in occupied kuwait in 
which three frenchmen were abducted and diplomats were temporarily 
detained 
the council passed its seventh resolution condemning iraq last 
sunday when it denounced the violation of diplomatic privileges 
the next resolution sources said will extend the current naval 
embargo to air traffic block iraqi goods shipments among other 
nations and call on all nations to restrict the operations of 
iraqs embassies 
all countries would have to close their airspace to planes 
approaching or leaving iraq or occupied kuwait 
only flights carrying refugees out of iraq or kuwait or 
bringing in medical supplies and food specifically authorized by 
the security council would be allowed to travel to those nations 
planes could not be shot down that is banned by the 1944 
international civil aviation convention 
the resolution would also make it clear that the trade embargo 
resolution adopted on aug 6 covers commerce in services which 
will be specifically banned under the new resolution 
at least one western dredging company is still working in iraq 
and soviet president mikhail gorbachev said the 8000 or so soviet 
civil and military advisors in iraq were working there on service 
contracts 
