even before the crisis triggered by iraqs aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait the cia was concerned about saddams links to palestinian 
terrorists who have attacked western targets cia director william 
h webster said in the text of a new york speech 
now he has both strong ties to palestinian terrorists and an 
elaborate network within his own intelligence service capable of 
planning and carrying out terrorist attacks against a variety of 
international targets webster told the foreign policy 
association 
but the intelligence official added that capability whether 
in iraq or in other nations is easier to measure than intent 
knowing the intent of world leaders requires the knowledge 
that comes from human intelligence which is often difficult ot 
acquire he said 
webster said h is putting additional emphasis on the cias 
human intelligence capability to measure the intentions of 
leaders involved in conflicts he gave no details of how such 
information might be acquired 
iraqs sizable stockpile of chemical and biological weapons is 
the largest in the third world and can be delivered by a wide 
variety of weapons including bombs shells and artillery rockets 
webster said 
what is even more troubling is iraqs ambitious missile 
development program the most aggressive and advanced in the arab 
world he added 
in general weapons of mass destruction are becoming easier to 
obtain and terrorism could extend the battlefield worldwide in 
future conflicts webster said 
based on intelligence assessments of iraq webster said united 
nations sanctions have cut off 95 percent of iraqs oil exports and 
halted its efforts to recover from the eightyear war with iran 
the exodus of thousands of foreign workers he said has 
hampered nearly all of iraqs domestic industries 
webster said the cia gets regular reports on more than 60 iraqi 
army divisions and on every tanker in iraqs merchant marine fleet 
as well as information about the effectiveness of economic 
sanctions and the condition of foreign hostages in iraq and kuwait 
cia agents also are looking at us relations with other arab 
countries whose populations saddam is trying to influence 
saddams ability to sway arab public opinion to convince 
them that he is the hero of the masses could over time 
destabilize the region webster said 
on us relations with the soviet union webster said the recent 
helsinki summit between president bush and soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev indicates a new world order 
but he said some concerns remain over soviet actions including 
concerns among some asian nations over the fact that reductions of 
forces in soviet asia have been slower than those in areas near 
europe 
in this era of new relationships however an understanding 
between moscow and some of these asian countries is likely 
webster said 
