<TEXT>
robert rhodes never knew his 
greatgrandfather elisha hunt rhodes but listened intently when 
his father told stories about their ancestors civil war exploits 
this month the rest of the country will hear about those 
exploits in words the rhode island volunteer wrote from the 
battlefields 
rhodes is one of the main characters of the pbs miniseries 
the civil war which will be broadcast beginning sunday 
filmmaker ken burns searched all over the country for photos and 
accounts of the fighting and found a gem not more than a mile from 
his southwestern new hampshire home it was a collection of rhodes 
letters and diary entries compiled by robert rhodes a college 
librarian who had inherited them in the mid1960s 
here in my own home town was this soldier who could epitomize 
the northern grunt the struggle of the ordinary man burns 
said 
rhodes enlisted as a private at age 19 after the first shots at 
fort sumter he was mustered out in 1865 as a colonel after 
witnessing major battles and the surrender at appomattox 
he learned to be a soldier in providence 
we drilled all day and night he wrote in 1861 standing 
before a long mirror i put in many hours of weary work and soon 
thought myself quite a soldier i was elected first sergeant much 
to my surprise just what a first sergeants duties might be i had 
no idea 
rhodes said the film brings his greatgrandfather to life 
it put him more in the context of his times which was good 
for me he said i think we are the product of our times and i 
had to overcome that some of his remarks might be called racist 
now 
he said his dad told stories of visiting elisha as a youngster 
and hearing stories about johnny mud a union soldier whom 
rhodes believes was elisha himself they were bogged down in the 
mud quite a lot 
rhodes noted that his family tree would have stopped growing in 
the civil war if elisha hadnt survived 
it shows how one person can make quite a difference hundreds 
of peoples lives were affected and thats just family members 
well never know who he may have shot whose other families he may 
have changed 
rhodes said his ancestor made no direct mention of killing 
anyone he would just say we had lot of bad dirty work to do 
today and we did it 
when writing of hardship he often said he didnt mind because 
it was all for the union which is also the title of the 
published collection 
elisha hunt rhodes returned to providence after the war where 
he held a number of veterans and community posts and was even 
urged to run for governor he was an internal revenue service 
official from 1875 to 1885 and the citys tax assessor in 1887 
he also was a member of the school board and an official of the 
central baptist church where there is a stained glass window in 
his memory he died in 1917 at age 75 
