graffiti bridge paisley park prince 
 
prince is back lets haul out the adjectives thrilling 
audacious breathtaking frustrating aggravating they all apply 
in fact they all apply to the first 17 songs on graffiti 
bridge setting this albums tone cant stop this feeling i 
got is a unique combination of 50s rock and 90s funk that 
immediately indicates prince is taking this project seriously but 
just when you expect the song to kick into overdrive comes an 
annoying slow break ushered in with the prophetic words pardon 
me for living but this is my world you cant make me change 
ok were willing to accept prince on his own terms he hears 
things others dont tries things others wont when he succeeds 
it opens the endless possibilities of music that retread workers 
such as mc hammer cant even comprehend 
thats part of what made batman so disappointing for prince 
fans it was paintbynumbers funk seemingly written in princes 
sleep the preceding lovesexy may have been an ungodly mess 
but at least he was trying 
graffiti bridge is a comeback because prince indulges 
himself while still worrying about public taste and the exciting 
moments simply outnumber the boring 
lets catalog some of the successes shake is an updated 
trashy rocker from the 60s with a huge beat love machine 
sizzles with morris day and elisas sexy dialogue the stately 
voice of mavis staples combines deliciously with princes 
playfulness on melody cool 
round and round sung by the youthful tevin campbell is a 
mesmerizing piece of funky reggae graffiti bridge is a ballad 
that compares favorably with purple rain 
prince is usually a doityourself musician but he benefits 
here from collaborations particularly with his minneapolis cohorts 
in the time who are at the top of their game 
the 68minute disc is not without its disappointments we can 
funk the fascinating collaboration with george clinton comes 
out sounding better in theory than in practice elephants and 
flowers and tick tick bang are unwelcome selfindulgences 
lyrically theres hardly a memorable moment here its a 
testament to princes musical ability that he can maintain interest 
despite this handicap the cosmic sexandspirituality dichotomy is 
showing frays around the edges 
and by the way what the heck is graffiti bridge guess 
well have to wait for the movie 
by david bauder associated press writer 
equals 
sitting pretty new world john mcglinn conductor 
 
john mcglinn has built a career out of resurrecting broadway 
musical comedy treasures of the past the conductor and musical 
archivist has had his greatest success with a complete recording of 
show boat a monumental effort that will be the definitive 
version of the musical for years to come 
now he has tackled sitting pretty an almost unknown jerome 
kern musical that the composer wrote in 1924 three years before 
show boat much of the score was missing for years turning up 
only eight years ago in a secaucus nj warehouse and while 
sitting pretty isnt the groundbreaking masterpiece show 
boat is the musical deserves the attention and love mcglinn has 
lavished on it 
the musicals book by guy bolton is sweet silly and 
irresistible so are the lyrics by pg wodehouse the plot 
involves orphans twins no less new jersey millionaires 
neerdowell nephews show girls con men and of course mixedup 
romances 
and kerns music is breathtakingly melodic ranging from 
touching romantic duets to toetapping comedy and dance songs much 
of the score and its all here in more than 100 minutes of 
playing time is rooted in the conventions of the time still you 
can hear the composer trying to break out of the straitjacket of 
1920s musical comedy 
instead of stringing together musical numbers from the show for 
the overture kern composed what mcglinn calls a symphonic 
poem the overture is a musical train ride complete with 
whistle bell and the sound of a steam engine coming to a halt it 
mirrors a train trip that takes place between the first and second 
acts of the musical 
listen to the heros lament there isnt one girl and you 
can hear whispers of the blues that found their way into show 
boat or the simple yet affecting a year from today 
prefiguring such kern standards as ive told every little star 
and the last time i saw paris 
the cast is headed by young mostly unknown musical theater 
performers including judy blazer davis gaines paige ohara and 
jason graae they carry the majority of the score and all are 
superb singers 
mcglinn and substantially the same cast performed sitting 
pretty in concert last year at carnegie hall this year he did 
kerns the cat and the fiddle there lets hope it too makes 
its way into the recording studio 
by michael kuchwara ap drama critic 
 
 
standard time vol 3 the resolution of romance columbia 
records wynton marsalis 
 
wynton marsalis blew with technical virtuosity as a 19yearold 
trumpet player making his recording debut in 1982 form dominated 
soul and it was unclear where the long road ahead would lead 
through nearly a decade of playing and learning marsalis has 
sacrificed none of his technical prowess while adding life to his 
horn 
the evolution of marsalis soul to date can be found on his 
latest album a collection of 20 standards in marsalis earlier 
playing the smoky 3 am half light of the blues was an image 
here it is real phrasing and tone suggest light and shadow as 
marsalis explores the heart of the music 
it is no accident that this exploration is so successful given 
that marsalis father ellis is on piano to help guide his 
talented son marsalis the elder is at the heart of this record 
tutoring his young master in the fine art of subtlety the lesson 
seems well learned 
by james reindl associated press writer 
 
 
 
texas tornados reprise texas tornados 
 
african rhythms are terrific and the brazilian beat is burning 
hot but you could travel the world over and never find a more 
enticing sound than the one blowing in through americas own back 
door the texasmexico border 
and no one does texmex better than the texas tornados a 
genuine supergroup featuring freddy fender flaco jimenez augie 
meyers and doug sahm 
hearing fenders plaintive tremolo on the hearbreak ballad if 
thats what youre thinking is just one of the many pleasures of 
this 10song collection 
another is the bouncy vox organ of augie meyers whose stylings 
on the instrument were the signature of the sir douglas quintet a 
1960s band founded by meyers and sahm that produced the hits 
shes about a mover and mendocino 
accordionist flaco jimenez is perhaps the worlds bestknown 
player of the mexican polka and waltz music called conjunto 
sahm whose broad musical vocabulary encompasses all these 
genres stands solidly at the center of the texas tornados he 
plays a variety of instruments on the record and sings lead on more 
than half the songs 
sahm never hits a false note whether hes whooping it up on the 
cajunflavored who were you thinking ofor playing the part of 
an unrequited lover on she never spoke spanish to me 
texas tornados is one of those rare albums without as bad 
song its being played mostly on country stations but with a 
little wider exposure these gracefully aging sons of the southwest 
could cut a broad path into the mainstream 
by david dishneau associated press writer 
