<TEXT>
paul klee mortally ill knew that the end was near 
but he was determined to finish his work 
durchhalten keep going he penciled under a drawing he did 
three months before his death an exclamation mark was added the 
drawing portraying a contorted figure reflects the tenacious mood 
of the artist who had a prodigious ability to translate emotions 
into pictorial language 
fifty years after the genius of abstract art succumbed at least 
seven european museums have mounted commemorative exhibitions but 
the show at the kunstmuseum of his native bern is likely to remain 
unique 
it took the organizers two years to assemble virtually all the 
work klee completed in the last few months before he died june 29 
1940 aged 60 
he had been on what he once termed the tragic path since 
1936 when he learned that he was suffering from scleroderma a 
rare often fatal disease affecting the mucuous membranes 
that path was marked by an intensified pace in the work of the 
artist who was never idle in a career spanning four decades he 
produced some 9000 paintings waterolors and drawings 
the pace appeared to be fastest in 1940 the year of his death 
attesting to it is a catalog meticulously kept by klee himself in 
typical thoroughness it lists a total of 366 works finished in 4 
months on view at bern are 328 
many of the works are from the collections of his son felix an 
art historian who died three days before the exhibition opened aug 
17 and from the bernbased paulkleefoundation the exhibition 
runs through nov 4 
but almost 100 exhibits were assembled from museums and private 
collectors in the united states japan and europe klee foundation 
curator josef helfenstein who organized the show said only 10 
works could not be sent to bern being too fragile 
one drawing was destroyed in a fire 15 years ago in the united 
states and 27 could not be located despite intensive research 
according to helfenstein 
plenty of sheets of drawings have pointed the way and said 
the time has come klee wrote early in 1940 sensing the nearness 
of death the title of one tod und feuer death and fire 
seems to have foreshadowed his cremation sick man in a boat 
and rowing desperately are others suggesting death was the 
dominating theme 
but helfenstein says the show disproves the widely held belief 
that the thought of approaching death is reflected throughout his 
final oeuvre 
in many aspects this latest period is representative for his 
entire work he said 
to stress his point helfenstein notes that the last number on 
klees personal list is yellow house ii a rather mysterious 
than tragic motif cheerfully colored 
helfenstein says it is hardly a coincidence that klee whose 
symbolism is a main feature of many of his compositions completed 
exactly 366 works the curator notes that 1940 was a leap year with 
366 days 
klee must have supposed that in a figurative sense this was 
his leap year too he wrote in the catalog 
on may 11 1940 klee left bern for a sanitarium in southern 
switzerland where his condition suddenly worsened he never again 
touched his brushes and crayons 
i cannot be grasped in this world said a passage in his 
diary a few months before he died for i am as much at home with 
the dead as with those beings who are not yet born these words 
were later inscribed on the stone marking his grave at berns 
schosshalde cemetary 
there is no record of it but the final weeks of his life must 
have been also depressing because of the german blitzkrieg defeat 
of france 
klee of germanswiss parentage had left his fathers country 
in disgust when the nazis took over in 1933 the new leadership of 
germany where he had spent most of his career and where he had 
risen to international fame declared his works degenerate 
although most sources list him as a swiss swiss authorities 
never granted klee citizenship 
</TEXT>
