<TEXT>
one of the most popular songs on college 
radio stations these days is a partly fond partly unsentimental 
look back at youth from a man whos feeling his age 
the ironic success of we dont do that anymore hasnt 
slipped by david slutes coauthor of the song and singer in the 
arizonabased rock band sidewinders slutes is 27 years old 
if anything they shouldnt relate to that at all he said 
all the classic rock stations should be playing it for the older 
people 
we dont do that anymore is a hard rocking take on aging a 
subject rock n roll hasnt treated with particular grace in the 
past both in song and in real life 
its a tale of a group of college friends who stay up all night 
and drink wine with nothing but dreams and things on our mind 
advance a few years later to preoccupations with jobs and rent and 
its clear from the songs title those days are past for slutes and 
his friends 
you look back and say my god i miss those times he 
said but you also look back and say thank god im not doing 
those same things 
the tempered idealism of the song is an apt metaphor for the 
sidewinders own career slutes richard hopkins mark perrodin and 
bruce halper realized a dream when rca signed them to a majorlabel 
contract but theyre finding theres a lot of hard work and no 
guarantees involved in becoming a rock n roll success story 
that work recently involved networking at the new music seminar 
in new york city and their fourth appearance at a converted 
hamburger stand turned rock club in albany thousands of miles from 
home 
veterans of the punk rock scene in tucson ariz the 
sidewinders are trying to make it as a hardedged traditional rock 
band disdaining the heavy metal scene and the studied weirdness 
of many college radio favorites musician magazine described them 
as an unholy cross between rem and husker du 
sidewinders arent doing their own growing up in the obscurity 
that characterizes many similar bands 
the band put out its first album by itself and expected several 
other years of recording on independent labels before anyone in the 
big leagues noticed them slutes said instead rca signed them 
after seeing the band at a showcase in austin texas 
auntie ramos pool hall named after an place near where the 
band rehearses back home is the sidewinders second rca album 
were growing as songwriters and players with every album 
slutes said lyrically for me im writing a lot better im 
learning how to explain things better to music and mark is writing 
better music 
the brutally brief saras not sober is about impatience 
directed toward a drunken friend slutes charitably describes 
sara as a composite of several people he knows 
with we dont do that anymore slutes said he had to walk 
the fine line between making the song maudlin or a joke 
it comes about as close to any song weve done to life he 
said as you get older your priorities change its something i 
live with everyday 
the band produced auntie ramos pool hall themselves 
although rca recently pressured them to hire a manager and make the 
next record with an outside producer slutes said 
the company said look you guys you have to grow up youre 
not an indie independent band anymore he said 
but slutes appears to have picked up on the type of work bands 
have to do offstage to get ahead he quickly recites the call 
letters of local radio stations that have been playing we dont 
do that anymore he was following a recent interview with dinner 
hosted by an albany college radio station 
you look at radio and it seems its gone from being 
songoriented to being soundoriented having a certain production 
quality he said you dont seem to hear real songs anymore and 
were a real songoriented band 
that sounds kind of preachy but there are a lot of great 
bands out there that have good songs that you dont hear on the 
radio because they dont have the right sound we havent had a 
producer yet so we havent gotten our radio ear yet or whatever 
you need 
while hopkins jokes about sidewinders plans for world 
domination the band seems content with gradual career 
advancement 
were really happy especially at the college level with how 
weve been received slutes said we seem to have gotten a 
decent fan base now that so when we go to a town we have a certain 
number of people waiting to see us 
</TEXT>
