democratic congressional leaders today blamed 
the bush administrations demand to slash the capital gains tax for 
the breakdown of budget talks just two weeks from the start of the 
new fiscal year 
but president bush asked if capital gains was the stumbling 
block told reporters not as far as im concerned bush said 
he talked with his budget negotiators today and were going back 
were staying with it i cant really predict whats going to 
happen 
the problem is the insistence of the administration to reduce 
the capital gains tax house speaker thomas s foley dwash 
told reporters 
the real difficulty and the major obstable to agreement is the 
tax issue said senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine 
the rest would come together quickly 
participants said they still hoped to try to work out a budget 
deal but it was unclear how quickly they could do so 
congressional leaders planned to meet in the capitol today with top 
administration officials to discuss the impasse 
its not total gridlock said foley 
asked whether he was optimistic bush said everybody involved 
agrees weve come quite a ways but its not done by a long 
shot 
republicans insisted that there were other important differences 
between the two sides over spending cuts but democrats insisted 
these were relatively minor democrats harped on their oftrepeated 
theme that a capital gains tax cut which republicans say would 
spur the economy would simply cut taxes for the wealthy 
its not quite an impasse but its pretty close to one 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said after the talks 
ended 
at this point weve reached an impasse said another 
bargainer sen phil gramm rtexas 
todays session in the capitol took on a sense of heightened 
urgency on oct 1 the start of fiscal 1991 the grammrudman 
law will slash the 12 trillion budget by about 100 billion 
unless a deficitcutting deal is in place a cut that deep would 
violently disrupt government services 
the breakdown of the talks at andrews represented a major 
disappointment to budget bargainers who initially hoped that three 
or four days of meetings at the airfield would solve the fiscal 
standoff that has lingered all year 
but after meetings scheduled during varying intervals since 
sept 7 neither dole nor gramm would rule out an eventual budget 
pact but neither could suggest how it could happen 
its going to be tough but its still not impossible and no 
one is giving up said dole the problem is were running out 
of time 
the most profound gap between the two sides was over president 
bushs insistence that the package include a cut in the capital 
gains tax rate the tax is levied on sales of property supporters 
say the reduction would invigorate the economy by spurring sales 
democratic leaders have long insisted that the idea would be a 
windfall for the wealthy who own most property they have said 
they would only accept a capital gains tax cut if other taxes on 
the rich were boosted in their final offer monday the democrats 
demanded that the capital gains rate remain unchanged 
the only way you can say were at an impasse is if you know 
you wont back off from the capital gains demand said a 
democratic official involved in the talks who asked to not be 
identified 
republicans complained that there were other important 
disagreements as well democrats wanted to rely on higher energy 
taxes for about 49 billion during the next five years seven times 
the amount republicans sought 
the gop offered to cut pentagon spending over the next five 
years by 170 billion below the amount needed to stay even with 
inflation democrats said their reduction would be close to that 
figure but offered to lock in cuts for only the first two years 
10 billion next year and 232 billion the following year 
republicans wanted to hold domestic programs to the rate of 
inflation over the next five years democrats wanted to increase 
that amount by 5 billion 
for benefit programs like medicare and farm price supports one 
of the fastest growing parts of the federal budget republicans 
wanted to reduce growth by 1233 billion through 1995 the 
proposed democratic cut was less deep to the tune of 27 billion 
the two sides also never reached agreement on how to control 
spending in future years for example they continued to clash over 
whether and how the grammrudman balancedbudget law should be 
extended beyond its scheduled 1993 expiration 
despite those differences the two sides had moved closer in a 
number of areas 
for example they had tentatively agreed to about 59 billion in 
tax increases said one official who demanded anonymity these 
included higher levies on beer wine spirits tobacco and luxury 
items such as fancy cars private boats and planes electronic 
equipment furs and jewelry 
they also agreed that about 25 billion in firstyear savings 
would come from new taxes and fees democrats wanted 130 billion 
in new taxes and fees over five years republicans 1381 billion 
and although the two sides still differed over the size of 
spending cuts the gap between them in each area was dramatically 
smaller than it was when the bargaining at andrews began 
without action next years federal deficit is expected to be a 
record 250 billion or more 
