<TEXT>
charles c cox an economist and former 
securities and exchange commissioner has been named chairman of 
the united shareholders association a nationwide shareholders 
rights group 
cox will succeed texas oil man t boone pickens who founded the 
group in 1986 pickens will continue his affiliation with the 
64000member group 
the appointment of cox who will take over oct 1 was announced 
late monday at the groups annual meeting in washington 
the group also announced its latest list of 50 major us 
corporations targeted for shareholder activism 
the 1991 target 50 list ranges from aerospace and automotive 
manufacturer alliedsignal inc to xerox corp 
united shareholders director ralph whitworth said the group 
plans to concentrate on four reforms confidential voting in 
corporate elections elimination of poison pill antitakeover 
devices shareholder approval of lucrative benefits known as 
golden parachutes paid to top management who lose their jobs 
as a result of a takeover and requiring companies to exempt 
themselves from state antitakeover laws that may apply to them 
those proposals will be introduced at the annual shareholders 
meetings of the targeted 50 companies 
through the target 50 program we are encouraging companies to 
enter into a constructive dialogue with their shareholders said 
whitworth in a statement issued by the group 
cox 45 the first economist to be appointed a member of the 
sec stepped down in september 1989 to join a chicago consulting 
firm 
he had been a member of the independent commission for nearly 
six years before that he had been the secs chief economist since 
september 1982 
before joining the sec staff cox served from 1980 to 1982 as a 
professor of management at texas aampm university and from 1972 to 
1980 as an economics professor at ohio state university 
</TEXT>
