soybean and corn futures prices edged higher in 
early trading today on the chicago board of trade after the 
government reported that development of those crops continues lag 
behind the normal pace 
wheat futures were fractionally lower in trading described as 
boring by paul sylvester of gerald inc a commodities trading firm 
in chicago 
the soybean markets early gains represented a turnaround after 
mondays steep losses 
analysts said the corn and soybean markets drew support from the 
agriculture departments weekly crop progress report which showed 
leaves dropping in 22 percent of the soybean crop as of sunday 
compared with an average of 39 percent for that date 
thirtythree percent of the corn crop was in the mature stage as 
of sunday compared with the average pace of 61 percent the usda 
said 
the soybean complex also was supported by rumors that pakistan 
bought us soybean oil overnight and that taiwan may be in the 
market for soybeans 
in early trading wheat futures were unchanged to cent lower 
with the contract for delivery in september at 260 a bushel 
corn futures were unchanged to 1 cent higher with september at 
236 a bushel oats were cent lower to cent higher with 
september at 110 a bushel soybeans were 1 cents to 2 cents 
higher with september at 617 a bushel 
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading 
on the chicago mercantile exchange extending mondays strong gains 
amid continued strength in the cash markets 
