for uniteds parent ual corp according to a published report 
today 
the wall street journal said the new offer the latest in a 
series of onagain offagain deals for one of the nations biggest 
airlines could amount to 175 a share to 180 a share or 382 
billion to 392 billion 
that would be well below the 201 a share or 438 billion 
offer from a labor group that uals board accepted last april that 
pact has been scuttled by the financial uncertainty created by the 
crisis in the middle east 
citing unidentified officials close to the proposed deal the 
newspaper said the new offer probably will include participation by 
a foreign airline 
the story said a logical possibility would be british airways 
plc which was a principal equity investor in a 300ashare 
labormanagement bid that collapsed last october 
the journal story said british air declined to comment and 
leaders of the buyout group declined to identify the foreign 
carriers they say have expressed interest in backing the new offer 
last week a united airlines workers group announced it was 
ending an agreement with an investment partnership to acquire ual 
in a filing friday with the securities and exchange commission 
the worker group united employee acquisition corp said it was 
still interested in acquiring the chicagobased airline however 
the disclosure ended an agreement between ueac and coniston 
partners in april to help ueac a company formed by uniteds 
unions acquire ual 
the wall street journal story said the unions have invited about 
two dozen banks to this weeks meeting where their financial 
advisers are expected to outline plans for a new offer consisting 
of cash and securities 
one individual familiar with the agenda the story said 
cautioned that plans for the new offer are still evolving and are 
subject to change 
it also noted that it was unclear how the ual board will greet a 
lower offer 
