<DOCNO> AP900918-0228 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a top american trade official said tuesday that 
the united states is ready to relax its demands for abolishing farm 
export subsidies a step that could help resolve a dispute 
threatening world trade talks 
us trade representative carla hills said that washington would 
propose reductions of up to 70 percent in domestic farm supports 
and import duties and more than 70 percent in export assistance 
the proposal is to be submitted to the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade which is sponsoring the latest round of trade 
liberalization talks the talks are to conclude early december 
the 105nation negotiations launched in uruguay four years ago 
are deadlocked because of disagreement between the united states 
and the european community over farm supports 
there also are significant differences on how to liberalize 
trade in textiles and over the scope of new rules to cover trade in 
services such as banking 
on textiles hills said that the united states was ready to 
accept that the existing system of protection should be phased out 
but she defended the us view that aviation should be exempt from 
a services agreement 
at the heart of the farm trade dispute is the ecs refusal to 
dismantle its system of export subsidies to help farmers compete on 
foreign markets the united states backed by farm exporting 
nations led by australia has until now insisted on a complete 
phaseout 
a text being used as the basis of negotiations in geneva 
provides for substantial progressive reductions in support 
with the greatest cuts in export subsidies 
hills said the us proposal would achieve the goal all 
proposals have to be submitted to gatt by october 15 
trade ministers are to meet in brussels for final talks in less 
than two months hills was in geneva with a delegation of top us 
businessmen on the first leg of a weeklong european trip 
she dismissed an ec proposal for overall reductions of 30 
percent as inadequate adding that the 12nation trading bloc 
wanted to use as abase year 1986 when levels of support were 
particularly high 
hills said the united states would compromise on a method of 
liberalizing trade in textiles if that pushes us further down the 
road toward an agreement 
third world textile exporters have argued that trade worth some 
177 billion annually should be liberalized by winding down an 
existing system under which import quotas are fixed in bilateral 
deals 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

