<TEXT>
the jump in oil prices caused by the persian 
gulf crisis should make big oil companies at least a little fatter 
but the size of any windfalls will vary experts say 
companies that pump plenty of their own crude should bring in 
the most extra cash for the third quarter those more heavily 
involved in selling refined products such as gasoline will not fare 
as well 
major oil companies like other corporations refuse to make 
public predictions of their earnings 
but this fall when big oil reports its profits from the weeks 
following iraqs invasion of kuwait industry observers will have a 
heightened interest in the bottom line 
the political turmoil in the mideast has pushed oil prices to 
the highest levels since the mid 1980s and there have been 
warnings of a public outcry if oil companies appear to be making 
too much money by exploiting the situation 
analysts predict stronger earnings although the size remains 
uncertain some say oil companies might try to lessen the potential 
negative publicity from higher earnings by setting aside more money 
into reserve funds that will be used for such items as future 
litigation or oilspill containment 
the companies are going to be very sensitive to the public 
view of making profits or larger profits in this environment 
said jim murchie an oil analyst with sanford c bernstein amp co 
inc 
they will scour their liabilities and reserve requirements and 
maybe take larger reserves for cleanups and that kind of thing 
so as to serve if you will to dampen the reported earnings 
murchie said tuesday they have to not be seen to be profiteering 
from this and theyre really not if you look at these earnings 
theyre really getting hammered at the pump 
although oil companies are making more money for the crude they 
sell they also end up paying more for the oil they buy the full 
costs of higher crude have not been passed on to consumers who buy 
gasoline which cuts the profit margins of retail operations 
other industry observers doubt the companies will seek to dilute 
higher profits through fancy accounting techniques saying such a 
move would be easily detected by critics 
i dont think therell be any special shenanigans among the 
big guys said professor james m patterson of the indiana 
university school of business that would be so obvious that it 
would be more trouble for them than to just show the increased 
profits 
even though the price of oil has shot up from about 20 per 
barrel to more than 30 per barrel since iraq invaded kuwait aug 
2 analysts are divided over how much money that will mean for the 
majors 
for companies that are sensitive to crude oil prices its 
going to be very good said philip l dodge an oil analyst with 
nomura securities international inc for refiners its going to 
be temporarily lower for the quarter they havent been able to 
pass on all the increase 
robin shoemaker at shearson lehman brothers inc does not think 
the companies will be able to turn profits that are notably bigger 
in terms of earnings theyre going to show very modest if any 
improvement over the second quarter shoemaker said 
but even companies that are heavily involved in the 
lessprofitable businesses such as retail gasoline sales should 
come out of the oil crisis with a better bottom line patterson 
said 
basically theres been a windfall due to the increase in 
price and the increase in demand as well patterson said 
