african countries tuesday appealed for the return 
of export quotas to lift and stabilize the depressed price of 
coffee because of the huge losses they are suffering in the 
present free market for beans 
the objective of the continents producers was a new 
international coffee agreement among exporting and importing 
countries to regulate supplies and prices said filomeno ceita the 
angolan president of the 25nation interafrican coffee 
organization 
he said african producing countries had lost 12 billion in 
export revenue since the suspension 15 months ago of the present 
coffee agreements export quota system which stabilized prices by 
matching supplies to demand 
colombia the worlds secondbiggest producer behind brazil 
also wanted to see quotas back under a new pact said jorge 
cardenas the countrys chief coffee executive 
the main obstacle to the opening of negotiations on a new coffee 
pact was uncertainty over brazils position said ceita who is 
attending a twoweek meeting here of the 72nation international 
coffee organization 
no new pact could work effectively without the participation of 
the worlds biggest producer and exporter delegates said 
brazil is expected to disclose its attitude toward calls for 
negotiations on a new international agreement next week when the 
head of its delegation arrives for producerconsumer talks 
the coffee organization meeting opened sept 17 and is 
scheduled to end sept 28 
the present coffee agreement which lacks powers to regulate 
supplies and prices expires sept 30 1991 
