<TEXT>
general motors corp will spend 42 billion to 
protect employees incomes but remains free to close factories 
under a tentative agreement with the united auto workers union a 
newspaper reported 
in an industry threatened by a sluggish economy and growing 
foreign competition the threeyear pact reached after a weekend of 
roundtheclock negotiations signaled to some the dawning of a new 
era in us automaking 
we feel the spirit we developed during the negotiations bodes 
well for general motors the customer and the marketplace said 
gm vice president alfred warren 
many on the union side too were hopeful even though details 
of the threeyear pact were delayed until tuesday 
i was kind of scared we were going to be off today but since 
we settled im glad said jd boatman 61 a worker at gms 
cadillac plant in detroit 
the last major strike was six years ago when the union struck 
selected gm plants for a week 
the detroit free press reported in its tuesday editions that the 
agreement contains 42 billion in income guarantees eliminates 
weak plantclosing prohibitions from the previous agreement and 
increases wages by 3 percent the first year 
the agreement also provides for lumpsum payments equal to 3 
percent of wages in the second and third years and increases 
monthly pensions from 1500 to 1800 for workers who retire after 
30 years according to union and company officials who spoke to the 
newspaper on the condition of anonymity 
health insurance provisions remain unchanged the officials 
said 
the union and the no 1 us automaker negotiated well past the 
midnight friday expiration of the old contract and produced a 
tentative settlement after 41 hours of nonstop talks 
uaw president owen bieber said details of the agreement had to 
be delayed until the information could get out to the 300000 
affected union members the tentative settlement was announced 
after 2 am 
therefore we couldnt proceed without having the normal 
material that we would provide for them before they made a decision 
on the recommended agreement he said 
about 300 members of the uaws gm bargaining council met 
privately in suburban dearborn monday but postponed review of the 
agreement until tuesday morning in detroit 
the absence of public posturing was conspicuous in these talks 
which were conducted under a news blackout in the final stages but 
gm and the uaw may need all the cordiality they can muster to get 
through the next three years 
gm faces the prospect of shrinking its number of factories 
