<TEXT>
eastman kodak cos new photographic 
compact disc system is a shrewd move to preserve the companys 
traditional film market while taking advantage of new electronic 
technologies industry watchers said tuesday 
concerns about the threat to kodak from electronic imaging 
will subside for a while said eugene glazer an analyst with 
dean witter reynolds 
the photo cd system introduced tuesday at news conferences in 
new york london tokyo and rochester is being developed jointly 
with dutch electronics company nv philips the system stores 
photographic images from standard 35 millimeter film onto compact 
discs and the pictures can then be replayed on television screens 
the system will be available in 1992 kodak said 
as was obvious at kodaks product demonstration photographs 
taken on film are still far superior to those taken electronically 
nothing even remotely comes close to conventional film and 
photo papers in terms of quality and price said barry harrand 
director of marketing research for the michiganbased photo 
marketing association 
the photo cd system is kodaks first consumer product that 
combines conventional picturetaking with the conveniences of 
electronics glazer said investors have been concerned about the 
threat posed to kodaks basic silverhalide film business by new 
technologies he said 
theyve essentially successfully defended the role of silver 
halide technology as the capture medium said mark obenzinger an 
analyst with trinity trading co 
most analysts said it was too early to predict how many people 
will want to watch their photographs on television there may be 
more demand for the systems applications in desktop publishing 
said financial analyst brenda landry of new yorks morgan stanley 
kodak officials said the system could be made accessible to almost 
any computer 
it can make virtually any computer an electronic fullcolor 
photo editing workstation said larry matteson vice president 
and general manager of kodaks imaging information systems 
obenzinger said the system is wellpriced for both consumers and 
photofinishers kodak estimated that the photo disc players which 
would also plays audio discs would cost less than 500 while the 
discs would cost less than 20 
the photofinishing system including a discwriter computer 
thermal printer would cost about 100000 kodak said 
a 1988 survey by the photo marketing association showed that 57 
percent of americans would be interested in looking at their 
photographs on television harrand said 
harrand said he expects to see all kinds of hybrid technologies 
introduced onto the photographic market in the next few years 
he said he expects such systems should expand the market for 
photo sales as consumers gain more control over what they can do 
with their photographs 
