<TEXT>
general motors corp threw more than 4 billion 
at the united auto workers to mollify labor and clear the way for 
closing unprofitable plants under a threeyear deal the unions 
bargaining council approved tuesday 
the worlds largest automaker will make the money available to 
assure workers will be paid if they are laid off when plants close 
analysts say such closings are inevitable if gm is to become more 
competitive and regain market share lost to us and foreign 
rivals 
the union made job security its top priority in this years 
talks and said that objective was achieved in the talks with gm 
job security and income security go handinhand when you make 
the income security so high that they have got to make sure that 
theyre going to work on job security uaw vice president stephen 
yokich said 
gm closed four assembly plants in the last three years putting 
about 9000 employees out of work the 1987 contract language that 
allowed the closings remains in the tentative agreement this time 
gm will pay dearly to close a plant an affected worker 
may be laid off for no more than 36 weeks from a plant closed 
because of slow sales of a product made there 
would be paid 95 percent of base wages from a companypaid 
supplemental employment benefits fund 
must be recalled after 36 weeks or be placed in a jobs bank 
also paid for by gm the jobs may have nothing to do with the auto 
industry workers could stay in the job bank for the life of the 
contract 
gm will spend 335 billion on the supplemental benefits fund 
and the jobs bank and 663 million on other incomeprotection 
programs the 300000 uawrepresented workers will vote on the 
contract over the next two weeks 
its a sweetened buyout based on the framework already in 
place said harley shaiken a labor professor at the university 
of california at san diego it gives gm a lot of flexibility 
the agreement also provides 
a 3 percent base wage increase in the first year and onetime 
payments equal to 3 percent of annual salary in the second and 
third years 
continued costofliving adjustments 
union officials said an assembler who now makes 1401 an hour 
would receive 1653 an hour under the new contract counting both 
the raise and costofliving increases based on an assumption of 
44 percent annual inflation based on that assumption the wage 
would rise to 1719 in the contracts second year and 1788 the 
third year 
bargaining council members who received details in a threehour 
meeting tuesday were largely impressed the contract will fly with 
the rank and file they said 
its an ok contract said local 594 president don douglas 
an outspoken critic of uaw leadership 
if gm shrinks as expected in the next three years so will the 
union 
here the uaw has achieved some measurable increase in job 
security at the price of accepting the continued erosion in 
employment levels shaiken said 
assuming approval of the agreement the uaw will move onto ford 
motor co or chrysler corp where negotiations have been suspended 
since aug 28 when the uaw picked gm as its bargaining target 
the union probably would prefer to take the pattern to ford 
next but that may depend on whether a canadian auto workers strike 
of fords operations there has been resolved the strike reached a 
fourth day tuesday 
i would think that unofficially wed be next in the barrel 
uawford vice president ernie lofton said 
chrysler in the worst financial shape of the big three has 
said it probably couldnt afford a contract tailored at gm or ford 
the no 3 automaker has plenty of cash on hand from the sale of 
subsidiaries and interest in other ventures but it needs the money 
to develop new cars and trucks buying out workers the way gm 
agreed to could leave chrysler cashpoor and with no new products 
bieber said he didnt know how much more this contract would 
cost gm than the 1987 agreement the income protection commitment 
alone is three times greater than the last contract however 
overall its a good agreement very solid said jerry 
melillo president of uaw local 1250 in cleveland and a member of 
the unions ford bargaining committee 
fords use of overtime to avoid building new plants in the 1980s 
is targeted in the pattern agreement the new contract would 
provide for a 5percent shift premium for some overtime work 
thats pointed directly at ford shaiken said those 
overtime provisions are meant to establish a pattern 
ford presented the caw with a new economic package tuesday but 
it was not favorably received 
the best i can say is it forms a basis for continuing talks 
not a basis for settlement caw president bob white said 
